default3.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGlobally, 
defaultchildren with disabilities are
default more likely to experience violence and abuse
default than children without disabilities
default.
default 
defaultResearch conducted in 
defaultCameroon, Ethiopia, Senegal, Uganda and Zambia 
defaultby the African Child Policy Forum, found that the almost 1
default,
default000 young people with disabilities had universally experienced, at a minimum, sexual harassment and emotional violence during their childhood. 
defaultThe per
defaultpetrators of violence were often members of their extended family or their peers, making the home and school often unsafe spaces for children with disabilities
default.
default 
defaultThe 
defaultAfrican Child Policy Forum research found that 
defaultacross the entire sexual violence category,
default girls and boys with disabilities were equally likely to suffer
default sexual violence once or twice (28% of all cases), but girls were far more likely to suffer sexual violence more than 10 times (28%) than boys (16%).
